item.title: Watch: Saturn emerges from behind the Moon in rare video
item.description: Astrophotographer Andrew McCarthy captured a dramatic video of Saturn emerging from behind the Moon and shared it on social media. Enhanced with an infrared filter for better visibility, the footage shows Saturn's rings as it reappears from the Moonâ€™s shadow. This phenomenon, known as occultation, has intrigued many astronomy enthusiasts and social media users.
item.dc:creator: TOI Science Desk

item.title: Hurricane Helene weakens to a Category 1 storm
item.description: Hurricane Helene has downgraded to a Category 1 storm with maximum sustained winds of 75 mph. Initially striking Florida as a Category 4 hurricane, it caused severe flooding and power outages affecting over 885,000 homes and businesses. Now moving northward to Georgia, the storm continues to impact thousands of residents.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Earth to get second moon from September 29 to November 25: How to watch
item.description: Earth is set to gain a temporary mini-moon this autumn with the arrival of asteroid 2024 PT5. The asteroid, measuring about 33 feet wide, will orbit Earth from September 29 to November 25 before leaving its gravitational pull. Professional telescopes will capture images of this rare occurrence, emphasizing the dynamic activity in our solar system.
item.dc:creator: TOI Science Desk

item.title: Justice or torture: Alabama execute Alan Eugene Miller by Nitrogen hypoxia
item.description: Alan Eugene Miller was executed in Alabama by nitrogen hypoxia for the 1999 murders of three men. He became the second inmate to die by this method. The execution, which lasted about 15 minutes, was described as going according to plan. This method has been criticized as potentially causing severe suffering.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Watch: Haitian President's UN speech goes viral after water pitcher mishap
item.description: During his UN speech, Haitian President Edgard Leblanc Fils became an internet sensation after spilling water on himself. The incident sparked viral memes but did not overshadow his call for global support to combat gang violence and human rights violations in Haiti. He also demanded reparations for historical injustices and addressed Donald Trump's controversial remarks about Haitian immigrants.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Plans underway for bronze sculpture honouring former Victorian premier Daniel Andrews
item.description: A bronze sculpture is being planned to honour former Victorian premier Daniel Andrews for his over 3000 days in office. This initiative follows a policy from the 1990s aimed at recognising long-serving premiers. The Victorian government has confirmed that planning is underway, with the Department of Premier and Cabinet initiating this process.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Shigeru Ishiba to become Japan's next prime minister
item.description: Shigeru Ishiba won the Liberal Democratic Party leadership election with 215 votes and is set to become Japan's next prime minister. Defeating Sanae Takaichi who secured 194 votes, Ishiba emphasizes his experience in tackling social issues. The LDP has governed Japan nearly uninterrupted for decades, often overshadowing opposition parties.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Boris Johnson gave 'manly pep talk' to Harry in bid to stop 'Megxit', memoir reveals
item.description: In his memoir 'Unleashed,' former UK PM Boris Johnson recounts his attempt to persuade Prince Harry to stay in his royal role through a 'manly pep talk' in 2020. Despite commending Harry and Meghan's contributions, Johnson found the effort futile as Harry was determined to step back from royal duties.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.description: Sean "Diddy" Combs has been arrested on charges of sex trafficking, racketeering, and prostitution. Authorities allege that his infamous parties were multi-day events involving drugs, alcohol, and forced sexual acts. Celebrities like Ashton Kutcher and KhloÃ© Kardashian have shared their experiences at these gatherings. Diddy has pleaded not guilty to the charges.

item.title: Countries with the highest Indian population including Mauritius, UK, Canada, and more
item.description: The Indian diaspora is a vibrant global community influencing various countries' cultural and economic landscapes. Key nations with substantial Indian populations include Mauritius, the United States, the UAE, Malaysia, Saudi Arabia, Myanmar, Canada, the UK, South Africa, and Singapore. The article details their contributions and celebrates their unique stories across these regions.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Vice-presidential debate between Walz and Vance: When and where to watch
item.description: Minnesota governor Tim Walz and Ohio senator JD Vance will face off in their only vice presidential debate on October 1. Moderated by Norah O'Donnell and Margaret Brennan, the event takes place in New York City and airs live on CBS News platforms. Both candidates are intensively preparing for this pivotal debate.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Trump set to meet Zelenskyy amid rising tensions over US backing Ukraine
item.description: Donald Trump is set to meet Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy on Friday morning, expressing confidence in brokering a peace deal with Russia. He criticized the unequal financial support from the US and EU for Ukraine. Meanwhile, Zelenskyy presented his victory plan to President Biden, who reaffirmed continued US support for Ukraine.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Extremely dangerous' Hurricane Helene makes landfall in Florida, major power outages reported
item.description: Hurricane Helene made landfall in Florida's Big Bend as a Category 4 storm with winds of 140 mph, leading to widespread power outages and flooding. Two deaths occurred in Georgia due to a possible tornado. Mandatory evacuations affected over 70,000 people. President Biden declared emergencies in several states for federal support.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Destroyed my life': Ex-rapper Shyne breaks his silence on Sean Diddy's role in 1999 nightclub shooting
item.description: Jamal "Shyne" Barrow, now a politician in Belize, accuses Sean "Diddy" Combs of ruining his life by making him the 'fall guy' for a 1999 nightclub shooting. Shyne served ten years in prison while Combs walked free. After his release, Shyne was deported to Belize and is currently the Leader of the Opposition.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Eating the cats' viral parody song on Trump gets over 9M views
item.description: A viral parody song targeting Donald Trump's assertion that immigrants are eating cats and dogs in Ohio has reached over nine million views on YouTube within 12 days. The revenue generated will support Clark County SPCA's efforts to find homes for stray animals in Springfield, Ohio. The artist believes music can unite people, especially when it involves animals.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.description: Several Iranian nationals have been indicted for hacking former President Donald Trumpâ€™s 2024 campaign, sharing stolen material with Bidenâ€™s re-election team. US authorities confirmed Iran's involvement in the cyber attack. The DOJ may announce charges soon, highlighting Iran's aggressive attempts to influence the election due to its national security interests.

item.title: 'No safety after certain hour': Ex Bad Boy executive on Sean Diddy's parties
item.description: LaJoyce Brookshire, a former Bad Boy executive, has made allegations about unsafe conditions at Sean Diddy Combs' parties, including nonconsensual activities and drug use. A circulating list links several celebrities to these events. Diddy is currently facing serious charges of sex trafficking and racketeering but has not pleaded guilty.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Infant killed after Chimpanzee snatches her from mother's arms
item.description: A tragic incident in Guinea saw a chimpanzee kill an infant after taking her from her mother, leading to an attack on a local research center by enraged residents. The event underscores how food shortages are driving chimpanzees out of protected areas more frequently, increasing the likelihood of human encounters and attacks.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'We will not leave': Palestinian President demands UN action to end Israel-Hamas war
item.description: Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas appealed to the UN General Assembly for urgent intervention to end the conflict between Israel and Hamas in Gaza. He highlighted the severe destruction in Gaza, calling for a ceasefire, humanitarian access, and Israeli withdrawal. Abbas also stressed that the Palestinian Authority should manage Gaza's borders and promised elections after peace is achieved.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
